# 4-bit Register (Sequential Logic) in Verilog

## 📌 Project Overview

This project implements a **4-bit register** using Verilog HDL, introducing fundamental concepts of **sequential logic design**.

Unlike combinational circuits (e.g., adders, ALU), this design demonstrates how hardware can **store state and update synchronously with a clock signal**.

---

## 🧠 Key Concepts

* Sequential Logic vs Combinational Logic
* Clock-driven state updates (`posedge clk`)
* Non-blocking assignment (`<=`)
* Enable control (`en`)
* Reset mechanism (`rst`)

---

## 🧩 Module Interface

```verilog id="8mmr4c"
module register_4bit (
    input        clk,
    input        rst,
    input        en,
    input  [3:0] d,
    output reg [3:0] q
);
```

### Signal Description

| Signal | Type   | Description                              |
| ------ | ------ | ---------------------------------------- |
| `clk`  | Input  | Clock signal (rising edge triggered)     |
| `rst`  | Input  | Reset signal (active high)               |
| `en`   | Input  | Enable signal (controls write operation) |
| `d`    | Input  | 4-bit input data                         |
| `q`    | Output | Stored 4-bit value                       |

---

## ⚙️ Design Behavior

```verilog id="f7dpvr"
always @(posedge clk) begin
    if (rst)
        q <= 0;
    else if (en)
        q <= d;
end
```

### Behavior Summary

* On **reset (`rst = 1`)** → register is cleared (`q = 0`)
* On **clock rising edge**:

  * If `en = 1` → load new data (`q ← d`)
  * If `en = 0` → hold previous value

---

## 🧪 Testbench

### Features

* Clock generation using `forever` loop
* Reset and enable control testing
* Sequential input stimulus
* Waveform-based verification

### Clock Generation

```verilog id="5x06za"
initial begin
    clk = 0;
    forever #5 clk = ~clk;  // 10ns period
end
```

---

## 📊 Expected Behavior

| Time | rst | en | d | q (after clk edge) |
| ---- | --- | -- | - | ------------------ |
| t0   | 1   | 0  | x | 0                  |
| t1   | 0   | 1  | 5 | 5                  |
| t2   | 0   | 1  | 9 | 9                  |
| t3   | 0   | 0  | 3 | 9 (hold)           |
| t4   | 0   | 1  | 7 | 7                  |

---

## ⚠️ Key Learnings

* Sequential circuits require a **clock signal** to update state
* `<=` (non-blocking assignment) is essential for correct timing behavior
* State is preserved between clock cycles
* Enable signals control when data is written

---

## 🔄 Comparison with Combinational Logic

| Feature | Combinational | Sequential |
| ------- | ------------- | ---------- |
| Clock   | ❌ No          | ✅ Yes      |
| Memory  | ❌ No          | ✅ Yes      |
| Example | Adder / ALU   | Register   |

---

## 🚀 Possible Extensions

* Parameterized register (N-bit)
* Asynchronous reset
* Register with load/clear control
* Integration into register file

